Numeric format literals

Numeric formats allow decimal values to be converted directly into their binary wire representation at compile time. They extend the existing decimal literal syntax with a format qualifier.

Unlike tagged built-ins (such as "ADD(... ; q4p4)"), which control how an operation interprets existing wires, numeric format literals control how a decimal value is encoded into bits.

Syntax

Unsigned decimal:

\value;format

Signed decimal:

\-value;format

where "format" is one of the supported numeric formats.

Examples:

Literal| Meaning
"\1.5;q4p4"| Encode decimal 1.5 as signed Q4.4
"\-2;q4p4"| Encode decimal −2 as signed Q4.4
"\1.0;fp16"| Encode decimal 1.0 as IEEE754 binary16
"\-3.25;fp16"| Encode decimal −3.25 as IEEE754 binary16
"\1.5;bf16"| Encode decimal 1.5 as Brain Floating Point 16
"\-2;bf16"| Encode decimal −2 as Brain Floating Point 16

The compiler performs the conversion during parsing and produces the corresponding wire bits.

---

Supported formats

q4p4

Signed fixed-point Q4.4 stored in an 8-bit wire.

\3.75;q4p4

↓

00111100

because

3.75 × 2⁴ = 60

Negative values use two's complement.

\-1.5;q4p4

↓

11101000

---

q8p8

Signed fixed-point Q8.8 stored in a 16-bit wire.

\12.5;q8p8

↓

0000110010000000

---

fp16

IEEE754 binary16 floating-point.

\1.0;fp16

↓

0011110000000000

\-2;fp16

↓

IEEE754 binary16 encoding of −2.

---

bf16

Brain Floating Point 16.

\1.0;bf16

↓

0011111110000000

\-2;bf16

↓

Brain Floating Point encoding of −2.

---

Decimal values

Integer and fractional values are accepted.

Examples:

\12;q8p8
\12.5;q8p8

\-5;q4p4
\-5.25;q4p4

\0.125;fp16
\1000;bf16

Scientific notation may also be supported:

\1e-3;fp16
\2.5e4;bf16

---

Relationship with hexadecimal literals

Numeric format literals convert a decimal value into bits.

\1.5;fp16

means

decimal value

↓

IEEE754 conversion

↓

16-bit wire

Hexadecimal literals represent an existing bit pattern.

^3E00

means

literal bit pattern

↓

16-bit wire

No numeric conversion is performed.

This distinction is identical to the existing decimal/hex behaviour:

Decimal| Hex
"\255" → numeric value| "^FF" → bit pattern
"\1.5;fp16" → numeric value| "^3E00" → FP16 bit pattern
"\-2;q4p4" → numeric value| "^E0" → Q4.4 bit pattern

---

Width

The resulting wire width is determined by the selected format.

Format| Width
q4p4| 8 bits
q8p8| 16 bits
fp16| 16 bits
bf16| 16 bits

Assignments using "=" must match the generated width exactly.

8wire a = \1.5;q4p4 ✓
16wire b = \1.5;fp16 ✓

8wire c = \1.5;fp16 ✗ width mismatch

---

Built-in compatibility

Numeric format literals only affect literal encoding.

Operations still use tagged built-ins to select arithmetic semantics.

16wire a = \1.5;fp16
16wire b = \2.0;fp16

16wire r,
1wire status
= ADD(a, b ; fp16)

The literal determines how the initial bits are generated.

The tag determines how those bits are interpreted by the operation.

---

Notes

- Numeric formats are compile-time conversions.
- The generated value is an ordinary wire after parsing.
- Decimal literals remain value-based.
- Hex literals remain bit-pattern based.
- Format qualifiers are independent of assignment width and cannot be combined with padding (";8") or signed-width ("\-3;8") suffixes.
